<p:notes xmlns:a="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/drawingml/2006/main" xmlns:r="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/relationships" xmlns:p="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/presentationml/2006/main"><p:cSld><p:spTree><p:nvGrpSpPr><p:cNvPr id="1" name=""/><p:cNvGrpSpPr/><p:nvPr/></p:nvGrpSpPr><p:grpSpPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="0" y="0"/><a:ext cx="0" cy="0"/><a:chOff x="0" y="0"/><a:chExt cx="0" cy="0"/></a:xfrm></p:grpSpPr><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="25602" name="Rectangle 2"/><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1" noRot="1" noChangeAspect="1" noChangeArrowheads="1" noTextEdit="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph type="sldImg"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="1249363" y="587375"/><a:ext cx="4835525" cy="3625850"/></a:xfrm><a:ln w="12700" cap="flat"/></p:spPr></p:sp><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="25603" name="Rectangle 3"/><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1" noChangeArrowheads="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph type="body" idx="1"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="953347" y="4563904"/><a:ext cx="5410199" cy="4328875"/></a:xfrm><a:noFill/></p:spPr><p:txBody><a:bodyPr lIns="95708" tIns="47854" rIns="95708" bIns="47854"/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:pPr><a:lnSpc><a:spcPct val="105000"/></a:lnSpc><a:spcBef><a:spcPct val="75000"/></a:spcBef></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>Software Governance is an interdependent series of components, owned by different organizations.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr><a:lnSpc><a:spcPct val="105000"/></a:lnSpc><a:spcBef><a:spcPct val="75000"/></a:spcBef></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>Pillar identifies a key component of the software governance process.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr><a:lnSpc><a:spcPct val="105000"/></a:lnSpc><a:spcBef><a:spcPct val="75000"/></a:spcBef></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>Description describes the main purpose of the pillar.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr><a:lnSpc><a:spcPct val="105000"/></a:lnSpc><a:spcBef><a:spcPct val="75000"/></a:spcBef></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>Tool identifies if an IT solution exists for that pillar.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr><a:lnSpc><a:spcPct val="105000"/></a:lnSpc><a:spcBef><a:spcPct val="75000"/></a:spcBef></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>Software Request &amp; Licensing is a tool to facilitate approval routing for software requests and at the same time, also tracks all approved/purchased software over the lifecycle of that asset.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr><a:lnSpc><a:spcPct val="105000"/></a:lnSpc><a:spcBef><a:spcPct val="75000"/></a:spcBef></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>Application Depot is the standard tool used to delivery software to a pc/laptop.    Other methods do exist for installation on a server, and other tools like the Engineering Software Store also exist for delivery/use of approved software.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr><a:lnSpc><a:spcPct val="105000"/></a:lnSpc><a:spcBef><a:spcPct val="75000"/></a:spcBef></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>But, no matter how the software is delivered, all 3</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" baseline="30000" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>rd</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t> party software is expected to have a record in SRL.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr><a:lnSpc><a:spcPct val="105000"/></a:lnSpc><a:spcBef><a:spcPct val="75000"/></a:spcBef></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>The last pillar represents reconciliation </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"/><a:t>…</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t> which is the main reason all the other pillars exist.  We must be able to prove compliant use of 3</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" baseline="30000" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t>rd</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" smtClean="0"><a:latin typeface="Arial" charset="0"/></a:rPr><a:t> party software. This pillar pulls all the inputs together to determine.</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp></p:spTree></p:cSld><p:clrMapOvr><a:masterClrMapping/></p:clrMapOvr></p:notes>